✅ 1. Generate .dot file: target/configuration-dependencies.dot

Install the sbt-dependency-graph plugin.

project/plugins.sbt
addSbtPlugin("net.virtual-void" % "sbt-dependency-graph" % "0.10.0-RC1")


Then run:

Generate DOT file
sbt dependencyDot


This produces:

target/scala-2.xx/configuration-dependencies.dot


If you want the full dependency graph including all configurations:

sbt dependencyDot::compile
sbt dependencyDot::test

✅ 2. Show actual SBT graph including evicted dependencies

To see evicted versions:

Full tree with evictions
sbt dependencyTree


Or more verbose:

sbt evicted


Or show dependency tree with conflicts marked:

sbt whatDependsOn <org> <artifact> <version>


Example:

sbt "whatDependsOn com.fasterxml.jackson.core jackson-databind 2.13.4"

✅ 3. Generate BDIO file + Detect diagnostics log

You need Black Duck Detect (Synopsys Detect).

Run Detect (SBT mode)
bash <(curl -s https://detect.synopsys.com/detect.sh) \
  --detect.tools=SIGNATURE_SCAN \
  --detect.project.name=my-project \
  --detect.sbt.included.configurations=compile,test \
  --detect.output.path=detect-output \
  --detect.diagnostic=true \
  --detect.bdio.output.path=detect-bdio

Output generated:
Artifact	Path
BDIO file	detect-bdio/*.jsonld
Diagnostics log	detect-output/diagnostic/*.zip
Standard log	detect-output/runs/*.log

The BDIO file is what Detect uploads to Black Duck server.
The diagnostics ZIP contains logs, dependency graphs, configuration data, etc.
